tional law. This critical analysis of the current state of the law makes the case that rather than leaving the judiciary to sort out what are essentially political issues, Canadian politicians need to take responsibility for this crucial aspect of building a just society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEskimosxCasesxLegal status, laws, etcxCanada. 0aEskimosxLegal status, laws, etczCanadavCases. 0aEskimosxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanadavCases. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCasesxLegal status, laws, etcxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etczCanadavCases. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanadavCases. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etcxCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077488022040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774880220423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774880220/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles